TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Determinants of Tariff and Nontariff Trade Restrictions in the United States
AU  - Ray, Edward John
Y1  - 1981/02/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260952
DO  - 10.1086/260952
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 105
EP  - 121
VL  - 89
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper develops and tests a simple model for the determination of tariff and nontariff barriers to trade across industries within the United States, using 1970 trade data. We find that nontariff trade restrictions have supplemented tariff protection in the United States. Both tariff and nontariff trade restrictions are biased toward industries in which the United States has an apparent comparative disadvantage in world trade and away from industries in which consumer welfare losses from protection would be great. We also find substantial evidence that tariff and nontariff trade restrictions predominate in industries with very different market characteristics.
AB  - This paper develops and tests a simple model for the determination of tariff and nontariff barriers to trade across industries within the United States, using 1970 trade data. We find that nontariff trade restrictions have supplemented tariff protection in the United States. Both tariff and nontariff trade restrictions are biased toward industries in which the United States has an apparent comparative disadvantage in world trade and away from industries in which consumer welfare losses from protection would be great. We also find substantial evidence that tariff and nontariff trade restrictions predominate in industries with very different market characteristics.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260952
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260952
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Inflation, Corporate Income Taxation, and the Demand for Capital Assets
AU  - Kopcke, Richard W.
Y1  - 1981/02/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260953
DO  - 10.1086/260953
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 122
EP  - 131
VL  - 89
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The demand for capital is not systematically related to either the level or the rate of change of "effective" income tax rates on corporate capital assets. Rising inflation during the last 10 years has raised the user cost of capital for durable assets relative to that for short-lived assets even though this inflation has raised effective tax rates for more durable capital less than for short-lived assets. Even with replacement-cost depreciation allowances, the level and pattern of investment incentives probably will continue to vary with the inflation rate.
AB  - The demand for capital is not systematically related to either the level or the rate of change of "effective" income tax rates on corporate capital assets. Rising inflation during the last 10 years has raised the user cost of capital for durable assets relative to that for short-lived assets even though this inflation has raised effective tax rates for more durable capital less than for short-lived assets. Even with replacement-cost depreciation allowances, the level and pattern of investment incentives probably will continue to vary with the inflation rate.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260953
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260953
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Monetary Approach to the Crawling-Peg System: Theory and Evidence
AU  - Blejer, Mario I.
AU  - Leiderman, Leonardo
Y1  - 1981/02/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260954
DO  - 10.1086/260954
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 132
EP  - 151
VL  - 89
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper develops and estimates a model of the joint determination of the exchange rate, international reserves, and the rate of inflation under a crawling-peg system. The framework presented, which is an extension of previous work on the monetary approach, generates short-run deviations from purchasing power parity that occur simultaneously with movements in both international reserves and the exchange rate. The model is estimated by full-information maximum likelihood on the basis of quarterly data for Brazil.
AB  - This paper develops and estimates a model of the joint determination of the exchange rate, international reserves, and the rate of inflation under a crawling-peg system. The framework presented, which is an extension of previous work on the monetary approach, generates short-run deviations from purchasing power parity that occur simultaneously with movements in both international reserves and the exchange rate. The model is estimated by full-information maximum likelihood on the basis of quarterly data for Brazil.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260954
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260954
Y2  - 2024/03/22
